.TH "ELOT --- Literate Ontology Tool for Emacs" "1" "" "" 
.RS
ELOT lets you author OWL ontologies in Org-mode, exporting to OWL
Manchester Syntax, HTML and PDF documentation, and running SPARQL,
ROBOT and rdfpuml against them from inside Emacs.

.RE
.SH "Preface"
.PP
ELOT --- the \fIEmacs Literate Ontology Tool\fP --- is a package for
authoring OWL ontologies in Org-mode.  A single Org file is both the
ontology source (tangled to OWL Manchester Syntax) and the published
documentation (exported to HTML, PDF, or Info).
.SS "Who this manual is for"
.IP \(em 4
\fBOntology authors\fP who want their ontology and its documentation to
stay in sync, automatically.
.IP \(em 4
\fBEmacs users\fP curious about how literate programming applies to
knowledge engineering.
.IP \(em 4
\fBNewcomers to OWL\fP who want a working ontology in front of them
before reading a 400-page semantic-web textbook.
.PP
No prior experience with OWL or Org-mode is assumed for Part I.
Parts II--IV assume you have completed the tutorial.
.SS "How to read this manual"
.PP
This manual follows the https://diataxis.fr/ \fBat\fP \fIDiátaxis\fP structure:
.IP \(em 4
Read custom-id:part-tutorial \fBat\fP \fIPart I\fP front-to-back the first time.
.IP \(em 4
Dip into custom-id:part-howto \fBat\fP \fIPart II\fP when you have a specific task.
.IP \(em 4
Consult custom-id:part-reference \fBat\fP \fIPart III\fP for lookups.
.IP \(em 4
Read custom-id:part-background \fBat\fP \fIPart IV\fP when you want to know \fIwhy\fP.
.SS "Conventions"
.IP \(em 4
\fIcode\fP face for CURIEs, IRIs, function names, file paths.
.IP \(em 4
\fI~C\-c C\-x r~\fP for keystrokes.
.IP \(em 4
\fIitalic\fP for new terms on first use.
.IP \(em 4
\fIM\-x command\-name\fP for interactive commands.
.SS "Getting help"
.IP \(em 4
Project home: \fIhttps://github.com/johanwk/elot\fP
.IP \(em 4
Issues and discussion: the GitHub tracker.
.IP \(em 4
The ELOT menu in any \fIelot\-mode\fP buffer lists the main commands.
.SH "Part I --- Tutorial"
.PP
This part is linear.  Read it in order; it walks a first-time user
through installing ELOT and building a small ontology end-to-end.
.SS "Installation"
.PP
The fastest path is via MELPA once ELOT is accepted there.  Until
then, install from Git.
.SS "Prerequisites"
.IP \(em 4
\fBEmacs 30.1 or later\fP.  ELOT uses \fIpeg.el\fP, which became a built-in
library in 30.1.
.IP \(em 4
\fBJava 11 or later\fP, required by ROBOT.
.IP \(em 4
\fBhttps://github.com/ontodev/robot \fBat\fP \fIROBOT\fP\fP, an OWL command-line tool.  Download \fIrobot.jar\fP from the
ROBOT releases page and note its path.
.IP \(em 4
\fBhttps://plantuml.com/ \fBat\fP \fIPlantUML\fP\fP (optional), for diagram rendering via \fIrdfpuml\fP.
.IP \(em 4
\fBProtégé 5.6\fP (optional), for cross-checking ontologies in a GUI.
.SS "Install ELOT from MELPA"
.PP
When ELOT is on MELPA:
.RS
.nf
\fC(use-package elot
  :ensure t)
\fP
.fi
.RE
.PP
That is the whole installation.  \fIelot\-mode\fP is autoloaded.
.SS "Install ELOT from Git"
.PP
Until the MELPA recipe lands, clone the repository and add it to
your load path:
.RS
.nf
\fCgit clone https://github.com/johanwk/elot ~/src/elot
\fP
.fi
.RE
.PP
In your \fIinit.el\fP:
.RS
.nf
\fC(add-to-list 'load-path "~/src/elot/elot-package")
(require 'elot)
\fP
.fi
.RE
.SS "Point ELOT at ROBOT"
.PP
Set \fIelot\-robot\-jar\-path\fP to the absolute path of your downloaded
\fIrobot.jar\fP:
.RS
.nf
\fC(setq elot-robot-jar-path "~/bin/robot.jar")
\fP
.fi
.RE
.PP
You can also customize it via \fIM\-x customize\-variable RET
elot\-robot\-jar\-path\fP.
.SS "Verify"
.PP
Open an Org file and run \fIM\-x elot\-mode\fP.  The ELOT menu appears in
the menu bar.  \fIM\-x elot\-version\fP prints the loaded version.
.PP
If something goes wrong, see custom-id:app-troubleshooting \fBat\fP \fITroubleshooting and FAQ\fP.
.SS "Your first ontology"
.PP
In this chapter you build a tiny ontology of \fIpets\fP from scratch.
By the end you will have:
.IP \(em 4
a working \fIpets.org\fP file you can re-tangle and re-export at will,
.IP \(em 4
a generated \fIpets.omn\fP ontology in OWL Manchester Syntax,
.IP \(em 4
the start of an HTML render of your ontology document.
.PP
Time required: 15--20 minutes.
.SS "Create the file"
.PP
Create \fIpets.org\fP anywhere in your filesystem and paste the
skeleton below.  Open it in Emacs and run \fIM\-x elot\-mode\fP.
.RS
.nf
\fC#+TITLE: A tiny ontology of pets
#+AUTHOR: Your Name

* Prefixes
,:PROPERTIES:
,:header-args:emacs-lisp+: :tangle no
,:END:

#+name: prefix-table
,| prefix | uri                                            |
,|--------+------------------------------------------------|
,| ex     | http://example.org/pets/                       |
,| owl    | http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#                 |
,| rdfs   | http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#          |
,| skos   | http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#           |

* ex:pets
,:PROPERTIES:
,:ID:       pets-ontology
,:ontology-iri: http://example.org/pets/
,:END:

A small example ontology used by the ELOT tutorial.

** Classes
*** ex:Animal
A living creature.

*** ex:Dog
,:PROPERTIES:
,:subclass-of: ex:Animal
,:END:
A dog is an animal.

*** ex:Cat
,:PROPERTIES:
,:subclass-of: ex:Animal
,:END:
A cat is an animal.
\fP
.fi
.RE
.SS "Tangle to OWL Manchester Syntax"
.PP
With point anywhere in \fIpets.org\fP, run \fIM\-x elot\-tangle\fP.  A file
\fIpets.omn\fP appears next to your Org source.  Open it; you should
see Manchester-syntax declarations for \fIex:Animal\fP, \fIex:Dog\fP and
\fIex:Cat\fP.
.SS "Sanity-check with ROBOT"
.PP
From a shell:
.RS
.nf
\fCrobot report --input pets.omn --output pets-report.tsv
\fP
.fi
.RE
.PP
ROBOT’s report should be empty (or contain only INFO entries).
Errors mean ELOT generated something OWL does not like; see
custom-id:howto-lint \fBat\fP \fILinting and syntax checking\fP.
.SS "Where to next"
.IP \(em 4
custom-id:tut-axioms \fBat\fP \fIAdding axioms and annotations\fP --- give your classes proper
definitions and relationships.
.IP \(em 4
custom-id:tut-export \fBat\fP \fIExporting to OWL and HTML\fP --- produce a polished document.
.SS "Adding axioms and annotations"
.PP
TODO --- expand.
.PP
This chapter extends the \fIpets.org\fP ontology from
custom-id:tut-first-ontology \fBat\fP \fIthe previous chapter\fP with:
.IP \(em 4
\fIrdfs:label\fP and \fIskos:definition\fP annotations on every class,
.IP \(em 4
a \fIdisjointWith\fP axiom between \fIex:Dog\fP and \fIex:Cat\fP,
.IP \(em 4
an object property \fIex:chases\fP with \fIrdfs:domain\fP and \fIrdfs:range\fP,
.IP \(em 4
an existential restriction: every \fIex:Dog\fP \fIchases some\fP \fIex:Cat\fP.
.SS "Annotations"
.PP
Use the \fI:annotations:\fP drawer key to attach annotations to a class:
.RS
.nf
\fC*** ex:Dog
,:PROPERTIES:
,:subclass-of: ex:Animal
,:END:
,:annotations:
,- rdfs:label :: "Dog"@en
,- skos:definition :: "A domesticated canine."@en
,:end:
\fP
.fi
.RE
